docs.abstract: In 1967, I dropped out of college to be an artist. Six months later, I was a violent radical. What happened?
docs.snippet: In 1967, I dropped out of college to be an artist. Six months later, I was a violent radical. What happened?
docs.lead_paragraph: In June 1967, in the freewheeling spirit of the times, I dropped out of Antioch College, in Ohio, and hitchhiked to New York. I was 19, mildly though not madly political. In junior high, I had joined civil rights demonstrations. Now I opposed the Vietnam War. But my ideology was simply the counterculture’s: peace and love, plus anything fun that could undermine convention.

headline.main: What I Saw on the Way to the Revolution

docs.abstract: We chose the gesture purposefully. Our bodies were like flags flown at half-mast to mark a tragedy.
docs.snippet: We chose the gesture purposefully. Our bodies were like flags flown at half-mast to mark a tragedy.
docs.lead_paragraph: In early 2016, I began paying attention to reports about the incredible number of unarmed black people being killed by the police. The posts on social media deeply disturbed me, but one in particular brought me to tears: the killing of Alton Sterling in my hometown Baton Rouge, La. This could have happened to any of my family members who still live in the area. I felt furious, hurt and hopeless. I wanted to do something, but didn’t know what or how to do it. All I knew for sure is that I wanted it to be as respectful as possible.

headline.main: Eric Reid: Why Colin Kaepernick and I Decided to Take a Knee

docs.abstract: The relatively unknown story of photography’s important role in the Chicano movement is featured in a new exhibition at the Autry Museum of the American West.
docs.snippet: The relatively unknown story of photography’s important role in the Chicano movement is featured in a new exhibition at the Autry Museum of the American West.
docs.lead_paragraph: From 1967 to 1977, La Raza, the Los Angeles newspaper turned magazine, provided a vital and dynamic forum for Chicano political and cultural expression. Employing a range of disciplines, including photojournalism, graphic art, satire, poetry and political commentary, it was both chronicler and participant in the Mexican-American struggle for equality and justice.

docs.abstract: As the nation debates football players’ kneeling during the national anthem, activists wonder whether issues of racism and police misconduct will be forgotten.
docs.snippet: As the nation debates football players’ kneeling during the national anthem, activists wonder whether issues of racism and police misconduct will be forgotten.
docs.lead_paragraph: While a debate over professional football players kneeling during the national anthem consumed much of the country over the weekend, a scene was playing out around St. Louis that drew far less notice. There, demonstrators protested the acquittal of a white former police officer in the fatal 2011 shooting of a black man, marching inside a mall and through the streets in daily protests over the case for more than a week.

headline.main: Black Lives or Bottom Line? Activists Ask What N.F.L. Protests Are All About
headline.print_headline: Protests Start a Dialogue,  But About What, Exactly?

docs.abstract: “Between the World and Me,” Coates’s treatise on black male life in America, catapulted him to prominence. Coates spoke to The Times about his new book, “We Were Eight Years in Power,” his year in Paris and what he’s up to next.
docs.snippet: “Between the World and Me,” Coates’s treatise on black male life in America, catapulted him to prominence. Coates spoke to The Times about his new book, “We Were Eight Years in Power,” his year in Paris and what he’s up to next.
docs.lead_paragraph: When Ta-Nehisi Coates’s first book, “The Beautiful Struggle,” was published in 2008, it landed with barely a ripple. At the time, Mr. Coates was a struggling writer. He had lost three jobs, and he and his family relied on unemployment checks, his wife’s income and occasional support from his father to stay afloat. By the time the book came out in paperback, his fortune had shifted slightly; he’d become a regular contributor to The Atlantic magazine, writing a blog that attracted a moderate but engaged audience.

headline.main: Ta-Nehisi Coates and the Making of a Public Intellectual

docs.abstract: After recent events in Charlottesville, Va., a London exhibition by African-American artists takes on a new dimension.
docs.snippet: After recent events in Charlottesville, Va., a London exhibition by African-American artists takes on a new dimension.
docs.lead_paragraph: LONDON — At first glance, the painting seems abstract: white shapes and streaks hovering irregularly across a night-dark background. But after a moment, the forms become clearer in this Norman Lewis painting, “America the Beautiful,” which immediately hits the eye as you enter “Soul of a Nation: Art in the Age of Black Power,” at Tate Modern. They are the peaked white hoods and flaming crosses of the Ku Klux Klan.

headline.main: A Tate Modern Show Examines Race in the U.S.

docs.abstract: Many cultural controversies are well worth fighting over. The president is a virtuoso of the other kind.
docs.snippet: Many cultural controversies are well worth fighting over. The president is a virtuoso of the other kind.
docs.lead_paragraph: The secret of culture war is that it is often a good and necessary thing. People don’t like culture wars when they’re on the losing side, and while they’re losing they often complain about how cultural concerns are distractions from the “real” issues, usually meaning something to do with the deficit or education or where to peg the Medicare growth rate or which terrorist haven the United States should be bombing next.
